From the provided code, it appears that there is a potential memory leak in the **GetChangedLedObjects** method due to the way you&#39;re updating the **myList** LinkedList. The method is intended to return a list of LED objects that have their **updateRequired** property set to **true**. However, instead of adding the LED objects meeting this condition to a new list, you are adding them back to the original list, causing a potential infinite loop and memory consumption.

Here&#39;s the corrected **GetChangedLedObjects** method:

    public LinkedList&lt;LED&gt; GetChangedLedObjects() {
        LinkedList&lt;LED&gt; changedLedList = new LinkedList&lt;&gt;();
        LinkedList&lt;LED&gt; myList = getLedLinkedList();
    
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; myList.size(); i++) {
            LED led = myList.get(i);
            if (led.updateRequired) {
                changedLedList.add(led); // Add the changed LED to the new list
            }
        }
        return changedLedList;
    }

By making these changes, you prevent the original LinkedList from growing indefinitely and causing a memory leak.


