The clearest way to express polymorphism is via an abstract base class (or interface)

    public abstract class Human{
       ...
       public abstract void goPee();
    }

This class is abstract because the `goPee()` method is not definable for Humans.  It is only definable for the subclasses Male and Female.  Also, Human is an abstract concept &amp;mdash; You cannot create a human that is neither Male nor Female.  It’s got to be one or the other.

So we defer the implementation by using the abstract class.

    public class Male extends Human{
    ...
        @Override
        public void goPee(){
            System.out.println(&quot;Stand Up&quot;);
        }
    }

and

    public class Female extends Human{
    ...
        @Override
        public void goPee(){
            System.out.println(&quot;Sit Down&quot;);
        }
    }

Now we can tell an entire room full of Humans to go pee.

    public static void main(String[] args){
